          <section class="prose">
            <h2>What is the slope of a line?</h2>
            <p>
              In analytic geometry, the <strong>slope</strong> of a non-vertical line is the ratio between the
              vertical change and the horizontal change. It tells you how many units the line goes up or down when you
              move one unit to the right.
            </p>

            <div class="formula-box">
              \[
                m = \frac{\text{rise}}{\text{run}}
              \]
              If you know two points \((x_1, y_1)\) and \((x_2, y_2)\) on the line,
              \[
                m = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1}, \quad x_2 \neq x_1.
              \]
            </div>

            <p>
              A <strong>positive</strong> slope means the line rises as you move to the right. A
              <strong>negative</strong> slope means it falls.
              A slope of <strong>zero</strong> corresponds to a horizontal line, while a vertical line has an
              <strong>undefined</strong> (infinite) slope because the run is zero.
            </p>

            <h2>Relationships between slope, angle and percent grade</h2>
            <p>
              If a line makes an angle \(\theta\) with the positive x-axis, measured in degrees, the slope and θ are
              related by
            </p>
            <div class="formula-box">
              \[
                m = \tan(\theta), \qquad
                \theta = \arctan(m).
              \]
            </div>
            <p>
              In civil engineering and road design it is common to describe slopes as <strong>percent grade</strong>:
            </p>
            <div class="formula-box">
              \[
                \text{grade (\%)} = 100 \cdot m.
              \]
              For example, \(m = 0.08\) corresponds to an 8% grade.
            </div>

            <h2>Sign and magnitude of the slope</h2>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Sign:</strong> determines whether the line is increasing (positive),
                decreasing (negative), horizontal (zero), or vertical (undefined).</li>
              <li><strong>Magnitude:</strong> \(|m|\) measures how steep the line is. Large \(|m|\) means a steep line,
                small \(|m|\) means a gentle slope.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              For many applications, it is useful to express the slope as a <strong>ratio</strong> such as
              “1:4” meaning 1 unit of rise for 4 units of run. This calculator reports both the decimal slope and
              a simplified rise:run ratio when possible.
            </p>

            <h2 id="faq-heading">FAQ – Slope and grade</h2>

            <h3>Can a vertical line have a slope?</h3>
            <p>
              A vertical line has an undefined slope because the run (change in x) is zero. In the formula
              \(m = (y_2 - y_1) / (x_2 - x_1)\) the denominator would be zero, which cannot be represented by a
              finite real number. The calculator detects this case and labels the slope as vertical/undefined.
            </p>

            <h3>What is a gentle vs a steep slope?</h3>
            <p>
              There is no universal threshold, but in many practical contexts slopes with an absolute value less than
              about 0.05 (5%) are considered gentle, between 5–10% are moderate, and above 10% are steep. For roads and
              ramps there are often regulatory limits on maximum grades depending on usage and safety requirements.
            </p>

            <h3>How do I get the slope from the equation of a line?</h3>
            <p>
              If the equation is in <strong>slope–intercept form</strong>
              \(y = mx + b\), the coefficient of \(x\) is directly the slope. If the equation is in
              <strong>standard form</strong> \(Ax + By + C = 0\) with \(B \neq 0\), you can rearrange to
              \(y = -(A/B)x - C/B\), so the slope is \(-A/B\).
            </p>

            <h3>Can this calculator be used for incline ramps and roofs?</h3>
            <p>
              Yes. If you know the vertical rise and horizontal run of a ramp, stair, or roof, you can use the
              “Rise and run” mode to compute both the slope and the percent grade. This is useful for checking design
              guidelines or code requirements related to accessibility and safety.
            </p>
          </section>

          <script>
            (function () {
              const modeButtons = document.querySelectorAll('.slope-mode-btn');
              const inputsPoints = document.getElementById('inputs-points');
              const inputsRiseRun = document.getElementById('inputs-rise-run');
              const inputsAngle = document.getElementById('inputs-angle');
              const inputsGrade = document.getElementById('inputs-grade');

              const errEl = document.getElementById('slope-error');
              const btnCalc = document.getElementById('slope-calc-btn');
              const btnExample = document.getElementById('slope-example-btn');

              const resContainer = document.getElementById('slope-results');
              const resSlope = document.getElementById('slope-m');
              const resRatio = document.getElementById('slope-ratio');
              const resAngle = document.getElementById('slope-angle');
              const resGrade = document.getElementById('slope-grade');
              const resInterp = document.getElementById('slope-interpretation');

              function showError(msg) {
                errEl.textContent = msg;
                errEl.classList.remove('hidden');
              }
              function hideError() {
                errEl.textContent = '';
                errEl.classList.add('hidden');
              }

              function setMode(mode) {
                modeButtons.forEach(btn => {
                  const isActive = btn.getAttribute('data-mode') === mode;
                  btn.setAttribute('aria-pressed', String(isActive));
                });
                inputsPoints.classList.toggle('hidden', mode !== 'points');
                inputsRiseRun.classList.toggle('hidden', mode !== 'rise-run');
                inputsAngle.classList.toggle('hidden', mode !== 'angle');
                inputsGrade.classList.toggle('hidden', mode !== 'grade');
                hideError();
                resContainer.classList.add('hidden');
                resInterp.classList.add('hidden');
              }

              modeButtons.forEach(btn => {
                btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
                  setMode(btn.getAttribute('data-mode'));
                });
              });

              function gcd(a, b) {
                a = Math.abs(a); b = Math.abs(b);
                if (a === 0 || b === 0) return 1;
                while (b !== 0) {
                  const t = b;
                  b = a % b;
                  a = t;
                }
                return a;
              }

              function formatRatio(m) {
                if (!isFinite(m) || m === 0) return '';
                const sign = m < 0 ? -1 : 1;
                const absM = Math.abs(m);
                const run = 1000; // scale
                const rise = absM * run;
                const riseRounded = Math.round(rise);
                const g = gcd(riseRounded, run);
                const rSimplified = riseRounded / g;
                const runSimplified = run / g;
                const signStr = sign < 0 ? '-' : '';
                return signStr + rSimplified + ' : ' + runSimplified + ' (rise : run)';
              }

              function currentMode() {
                let m = 'points';
                modeButtons.forEach(btn => {
                  if (btn.getAttribute('aria-pressed') === 'true') {
                    m = btn.getAttribute('data-mode');
                  }
                });
                return m;
              }

              function calculate() {
                hideError();
                resContainer.classList.add('hidden');
                resInterp.classList.add('hidden');

                const mode = currentMode();
                let m = null;
                let vertical = false;

                if (mode === 'points') {
                  const x1 = Number(document.getElementById('x1').value);
                  const y1 = Number(document.getElementById('y1').value);
                  const x2 = Number(document.getElementById('x2').value);
                  const y2 = Number(document.getElementById('y2').value);
                  if (!isFinite(x1) || !isFinite(y1) || !isFinite(x2) || !isFinite(y2)) {
                    showError('Please enter numeric coordinates for both points.');
                    return;
                  }
                  const dx = x2 - x1;
                  const dy = y2 - y1;
                  if (dx === 0) {
                    vertical = true;
                    m = null;
                  } else {
                    m = dy / dx;
                  }
                } else if (mode === 'rise-run') {
                  const rise = Number(document.getElementById('rise').value);
                  const run = Number(document.getElementById('run').value);
                  if (!isFinite(rise) || !isFinite(run)) {
                    showError('Please enter numeric values for rise and run.');
                    return;
                  }
                  if (run === 0) {
                    vertical = true;
                    m = null;
                  } else {
                    m = rise / run;
                  }
                } else if (mode === 'angle') {
                  const ang = Number(document.getElementById('angle').value);
                  if (!isFinite(ang)) {
                    showError('Please enter a numeric angle in degrees.');
                    return;
                  }
                  const rad = ang * Math.PI / 180;
                  m = Math.tan(rad);
                } else if (mode === 'grade') {
                  const grade = Number(document.getElementById('grade').value);
                  if (!isFinite(grade)) {
                    showError('Please enter a numeric grade percentage.');
                    return;
                  }
                  m = grade / 100;
                }

                let angleDeg = null;
                let gradePct = null;
                let slopeText = '';
                let angleText = '';
                let ratioText = '';
                let gradeText = '';
                let interp = '';

                if (vertical) {
                  slopeText = 'Undefined (vertical line)';
                  angleText = '90° or -90° depending on direction';
                  gradeText = 'Infinite grade (vertical)';
                  ratioText = '';
                  interp = 'The line is vertical: the run (Δx) is zero, so the slope cannot be represented by a finite number.';
                } else {
                  if (!isFinite(m)) {
                    showError('Computation produced a non-finite slope. Please check your inputs.');
                    return;
                  }
                  angleDeg = Math.atan(m) * 180 / Math.PI;
                  gradePct = m * 100;

                  slopeText = 'm = ' + m.toFixed(6);
                  angleText = angleDeg.toFixed(3) + '°';
                  gradeText = gradePct.toFixed(3) + ' %';
                  ratioText = formatRatio(m);

                  const absM = Math.abs(m);
                  let steepness;
                  if (absM < 0.05) steepness = 'very gentle';
                  else if (absM < 0.1) steepness = 'gentle';
                  else if (absM < 0.2) steepness = 'moderate';
                  else steepness = 'steep';

                  let signDesc;
                  if (m > 0) signDesc = 'positive (line rises from left to right)';
                  else if (m < 0) signDesc = 'negative (line falls from left to right)';
                  else signDesc = 'zero (horizontal line)';

                  interp = 'The slope is ' + m.toFixed(4) +
                    ', which is ' + steepness + ' and ' + signDesc +
                    '. This corresponds to an angle of approximately ' + angleDeg.toFixed(2) +
                    '° and a grade of about ' + gradePct.toFixed(2) + '%.';
                }

                resSlope.textContent = slopeText;
                resRatio.textContent = ratioText || 'Ratio unavailable or not meaningful for this case.';
                resAngle.textContent = angleText;
                resGrade.textContent = gradeText;
                resContainer.classList.remove('hidden');

                if (interp) {
                  resInterp.textContent = interp;
                  resInterp.classList.remove('hidden');
                }
              }

              btnCalc.addEventListener('click', calculate);

              btnExample.addEventListener('click', function () {
                setMode('points');
                document.getElementById('x1').value = '0';
                document.getElementById('y1').value = '0';
                document.getElementById('x2').value = '10';
                document.getElementById('y2').value = '2';
                hideError();
                document.getElementById('slope-results').classList.add('hidden');
                document.getElementById('slope-interpretation').classList.add('hidden');
              });
            }());
          </script>

